3D plots (surface) (Fig. 1
                           ) show the result of solvent conc., the temperature of extraction, and the time of extraction on TAC, DPPH, and ABTS activities. Various ethanol concentrations mainly affected the extraction of principal constituents. A linear increase in TAC, ABTS, and DPPH contents was observed as the ethanol concentration increased from 50 % to 80 %, with a maximum TAC ∼159 obtained up to 68 % concentration. After that, it declined significantly. The monomeric anthocyanin yield and scavenging activity increased by extraction time at nearly 73.7 °C; this effect was not prominent at lower (60 °C) and higher (90 °C) temperatures. Following the increase in temperature from 60 to 73.7 °C, there was a progressive rise in yield, which then declined when the temperature was further increased to 90 °C (Fig. 1). The higher TAC (159.22 mg Cy3G/100 g) and scavenging ability (>70 %) with increasing time and temperature during extraction might be due to increased water diffusivity into solids and enhanced desorption and solubility of anthocyanins [18,19,23]. In contrast, yield reduced (p < 0.05) as time and temperature increased beyond 63 °C, possibly due to the anthocyanin breakdown at high temperatures [19,24] and kept for a longer time (Fig. 2
                           ). Thus, the temperature of extraction and time of extraction profoundly influenced the TAC, ABTS & DPPH scavenging activity. These findings are consistent with previously reported results [18,23,25–27].
